A 25y/o South East Asian male medical student presented in our outpatient department in January 2018 with left-sided cervical lymphadenopathy. The patient reported small bulges along the left side of his neck for one month. Associated symptoms included one month of low-grade fever and fatigue. There was no history of night sweats or reported weight loss. A course of antibiotics two weeks earlier did not improve his symptoms. On presentation, the patient was hemodynamically stable with a temperature of 100.1°C, heart rate of 98 beats/min, respiratory rate was 18 breaths/min and blood pressure was 115/80 mm/hg. On physical examination there was diffuse left cervical and supraclavicular lymphadenopathy. Lymph nodes were rubbery, soft and mobile. There were no changes in hands, eyes or ears. His nose and throat examination were normal. On auscultation of the chest, breath sounds were normal bilaterally and normal heart sounds where present. The abdominal examination was also normal. Initial lab investigations included complete blood count with total and differential leukocyte count, metabolic profile, erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR) and lactate dehydrogenase (LDH). This was to rule out any possibility of lymphadenitis, or neoplastic disorder. On laboratory examination there was an increase in lymphocytes percentage (40%) but no leukocytosis and an increase in inflammatory markers including ESR and LDH (
).
